I"|<p>A <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/continuous-state-dynamical-systems-share-a-common-structure">dynamical system</a> can get entrained by its input, meaning that its <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/dynamical-systems-have-a-certain-anatomy">state and dynamics</a> (e.g. <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/dynamic-attention-enables-object-permanence">period</a>) get <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/cosine-similarity-is-magnitude-agnostic">aligned</a> to the input. However, this only happens when the <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/cluster-index-quantifies-internal-external-connectivity">internal connectivity is low and the external connectivity is high</a>. Additionally, it typically manifests after a <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/fleeting-note-persisting-resembles-memory-consolidation">transient period</a>.</p>
